  "prompt": "If space (the universe) is a sphere or saddle shape, then what is outside of that? What do you call the empty space outside that comes after?",
  "response": "The shape or curvature of the universe has been a subject of significant scientific investigation and debate. If the universe is closed and spherical, it means that it has finite volume with no boundaries; traveling far enough in one direction would theoretically bring you back to your starting point. If the universe has a saddle shape or negative curvature, it suggests an infinite, open structure.\n\nFor either scenario, modern cosmology typically describes the universe as encompassing all of space-time. There is no \"outside\" of the universe because the universe is defined as the totality of space and time, including all matter and energy. Asking what is \"outside\" of the universe presumes a concept of external space, but by definition, the universe is all-inclusive and there is no external space beyond it.\n\nEmpty space or vacuum within the universe is still part of the universe. The notion of an \"outside\" space would be inconsistent with current cosmological understanding. Hence, scientists do not define or label an external void outside the universe, as anything beyond the universe falls outside the realm of observable and definable space and time according to our current models.",
